<section xml:id="sec-angle-properties-of-a-circle-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Angle Properties of a Circle in Real Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.2 Angle Properties of a Circle
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Apply the angle properties of a circle in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->
     <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>To connect abstract circle theorems to physical layout planning, recognizing how angle properties control real-world spacing, structural strength, and sightlines.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>Organize learners into small design teams. Act as the "head project manager." Provide graph paper, compasses, and protractors. Guide teams to see how shifting a position along an arc alters or maintains an angle.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Learner Experience Sequence</title>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p><alert>1. Group Work Formulation:</alert> Form a design firm layout committee of <m>3</m> to <m>4</m> learners representing engineers to map out a municipal theater seating arrangement.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><alert>2. Materials Needed:</alert>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Architectural grid paper</li>
                                    <li>Drawing compasses</li>
                                    <li>Protractors</li>
                                    <li>Fine-tip markers (three colors)</li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><alert>3. Step-by-Step Activity Instruction:</alert>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>Draw a large circle representing the outer boundary of a round amphitheater, marking the center stage as point <m>O</m>.</li>
                                    <li>Mark two points on the back wall arc, labeling them <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, to represent the main spotlight rigs. Draw lines from <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> to the center stage <m>O</m> and measure <m>\angle AOB</m>.</li>
                                    <li>Pick three different locations along the audience balcony arc, labeling them <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m>. Draw the viewing angles from each seat back to the spotlights (e.g., <m>\angle APB</m>, <m>\angle AQB</m>, <m>\angle ARB</m>).</li>
                                    <li>Measure all three viewing angles with your protractor. What do you notice about the sightlines from different seats on the same arc? How do they compare to the spotlight center angle <m>\angle AOB</m>?</li>
                                    <li>Discuss as a group how a civil engineer can use this property to make sure different seats in a stadium get the exact same camera view width.</li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

